          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How does my down payment affect my monthly mortgage payment?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "A larger down payment reduces your loan amount. With a smaller loan, your principal and interest payment is lower, you pay less total interest over time, and you may avoid PMI. A smaller down payment does the opposite: higher loan amount, higher monthly payment, more interest, and often PMI until you reach at least 20% equity."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is PMI and when can I remove it?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Private mortgage insurance (PMI) protects the lender when your down payment is below 20% on a conventional loan. PMI is typically charged as a monthly fee based on a percentage of your loan amount. You can usually request PMI cancellation when your loan balance falls to 80% of your home\u2019s original value and it must automatically end at 78% under federal rules for many loans."
            }
