                A down payment is the portion of a home&#39;s purchase price you
                pay upfront in cash. The rest is financed with a mortgage. For
                example, on a $400,000 home with a 20% down payment, you would
                put $80,000 down and borrow $320,000.
              </p>
              <p>
                Lenders use your down payment to measure risk. A larger down
                payment means you have more equity from day one, which usually
                leads to better loan terms and lower monthly payments.
              </p>

              <h2>How this down payment calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates your monthly mortgage payment based
                on:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Home price</li>
                <li>Down payment (percentage or dollar amount)</li>
                <li>Interest rate (APR)</li>
                <li>Loan term (years)</li>
                <li>Estimated property taxes and homeowners insurance</li>
                <li>
                  Estimated private mortgage insurance (PMI) if your down
                  payment is below 20%
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>It then shows how changing your down payment affects:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your loan amount</li>
                <li>Your principal and interest payment</li>
                <li>Whether PMI is likely required</li>
                <li>Your total monthly housing cost (PITI + PMI)</li>
                <li>Your total interest paid over the life of the loan</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Loan amount</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Loan amount} = \text{Home price} - \text{Down
                  payment} \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  Monthly mortgage payment (principal &amp; interest)
                </p>
                <p>
                  For a fixed-rate mortgage: \[ M = P \times
                  \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(M\) = monthly principal &amp; interest payment</li>
                  <li>\(P\) = loan amount</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = monthly interest rate (annual rate ÷ 12)</li>
                  <li>\(n\) = total number of payments (years × 12)</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  Estimated PMI (if &lt; 20% down)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Monthly PMI} \approx \frac{\text{PMI rate} \times
                  \text{Loan amount}}{12} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How much should you put down?</h2>
              <p>
                There is no universal &ldquo;right&rdquo; down payment. The best
                amount depends on your savings, income stability, other debts,
                and how long you plan to stay in the home. Here are common
                benchmarks:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>3%–5% down:</strong> Typical minimum for many
                  conventional loans.
                </li>
                <li><strong>3.5% down:</strong> Minimum for most FHA loans.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>10% down:</strong> Reduces PMI and monthly payment
                  compared with minimums.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>20% down:</strong> Often eliminates PMI and can unlock
                  better rates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>0% down:</strong> Possible with VA or USDA loans for
                  eligible borrowers.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Pros and cons of a larger down payment</h3>
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                <div>
                  <h3>Advantages of a bigger down payment</h3>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Lower monthly mortgage payment</li>
                    <li>Less total interest paid over the life of the loan</li>
                    <li>
                      Lower loan-to-value (LTV) ratio and stronger equity
                      position
                    </li>
                    <li>Often no PMI at 20% down or more</li>
                    <li>May qualify you for better interest rates and terms</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h3>Drawbacks of a bigger down payment</h3>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Ties up more of your cash in your home</li>
                    <li>
                      Less money available for emergency savings or repairs
                    </li>
                    <li>May delay buying a home while you save</li>
                    <li>
                      Could miss other investment opportunities with higher
                      returns
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <h2>Down payment, LTV, and PMI</h2>
              <p>
                Lenders look closely at your
                <strong>loan-to-value (LTV) ratio</strong>, which compares your
                loan amount to the home&#39;s value:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                \[ \text{LTV} = \frac{\text{Loan amount}}{\text{Home value}}
                \times 100\% \]
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>80% LTV</strong> = 20% down (often no PMI required).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Above 80% LTV</strong> = less than 20% down, PMI is
                  usually required on conventional loans.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                PMI protects the lender, not you. It typically costs
                <strong>0.3%–1.5% of the loan amount per year</strong>,
                depending on your credit score, LTV, and loan type. This
                calculator lets you adjust the PMI rate to match your situation.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for choosing a down payment</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Keep an emergency fund.</strong> Aim to have at least
                  3–6 months of essential expenses left after closing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider your timeline.</strong> If you plan to move
                  within a few years, a smaller down payment may make sense.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Watch your debt-to-income ratio (DTI).</strong>
                  Lenders typically prefer a total DTI below about 43%.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Factor in closing costs.</strong> These can add 2%–5%
                  of the purchase price on top of your down payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ask about assistance programs.</strong> Many regions
                  offer grants or forgivable loans for first-time buyers.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is for educational purposes only. It assumes a
                fixed-rate mortgage with level monthly payments and does not
                account for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Adjustable-rate mortgages (ARMs)</li>
                <li>Changes in property taxes or insurance over time</li>
                <li>FHA mortgage insurance premiums (MIP) rules</li>
                <li>Closing costs, points, or lender credits</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always review specific loan estimates from lenders and consider
                speaking with a qualified mortgage professional or housing
                counselor before making decisions.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Down payment FAQs</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How much should I put down on a house?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Many buyers put 3%–5% down, while others aim for 20% to
                    avoid PMI. The best down payment is the one that keeps your
                    monthly payment affordable <em>and</em> leaves you with a
                    healthy emergency fund. Use the calculator to test different
                    scenarios and see how they affect your payment and total
                    interest.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is 20% down always better?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Financially, 20% down often lowers your payment and
                    eliminates PMI, which is attractive. But if reaching 20%
                    would drain your savings or delay homeownership for many
                    years, a smaller down payment can be reasonable, especially
                    if you have stable income and a strong emergency fund.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I buy a home with no down payment?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes, but only with specific programs. VA loans (for eligible
                    veterans and service members) and USDA loans (for qualifying
                    rural areas) can offer 0% down. You still pay closing costs
                    and must qualify based on income, credit, and property
                    guidelines.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    When can I stop paying PMI?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For many conventional loans, you can request PMI
                    cancellation when your loan balance reaches 80% of the
                    home&#39;s original value. Lenders must automatically cancel
                    PMI at 78% LTV if you are current on payments. If your home
                    has appreciated, you may be able to remove PMI sooner with a
                    new appraisal or refinance.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
